oward working-class people, they unintentionally helped to develop the contemporary concept of a degraded and "other" American underclass. While contributing to our understanding of the history of American social thought, Class Unknown offers a new perspective on contemporary debates over how we understand and represent our own society and its class divisions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aInvestigative reportingxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aInvestigative reportingzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPovertyxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aPovertyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial classes in mass media. 0aSocial classesxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aSocial classeszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorking classxHistoryx20th centuryxUnited States. 0aWorking classzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081476740540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814724293423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814724293/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK